Here are both approaches in .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string parameter**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");
}
```

**3. Navigate — passing the full object**
```csharp
var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", product }   // complex object via the overload
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

**4. Receive both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service using productId
        }

        // Approach 2: full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            // use product directly — no fetch needed
        }
    }
}
```

**5. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Passed via** | URL query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Survives URI serialization** | ✅ yes | ❌ no (in-memory only) |
| **Deep-link friendly** | ✅ | ❌ |
| **Avoids extra DB/API call** | ❌ | ✅ |

Use the string `id` approach for deep links and bookmarkable routes. Use the object approach when you already have the data and want to avoid a redundant fetch.
